segments.text: My name is Darlene Baker, and I'm a student at A&M.
And I am interviewing Miss Margie Presnell for an oral history interview in my class, cultural geography.
OK. First question.
Were you born here?
And if not, how did you arrive?
And why did you pick this area?
I was born and raised here in Brazos County.
And I was born in the southern part of the county.
picked this part because my parents had always lived here and continued to live here.
And in those days, children did not go away from home to work.
They stayed home and worked with their families.
That's perfect.
Go ahead.
Is that it?
Why did you stay?
Well, we stayed at home with our parents because in those days, children did not have the opportunity to take
vocational nursing or anything of that sort in the schools, because I went to a one-teacher school, and we just didn't have those kind of opportunities.
So we just lived at home with our parents, all lived in one big happy family, and all worked together.
Okay, I'm going to stop it right here.
Okay, Ms. Cresno, what other family lines are you related to in the surrounding area?
Well, I have a sister, the Arnolds, that lives here, and a sister that is deceased, and her family is still living here, and they are the Allens.
And I have a nephew, Robert Baker, that has a ranch out here, the other side of Curtin, and they are here quite often.
Come here quite often.
Okay.
Were there any disasters that you remember, such as floods, storms, or droughts, anything like that?
And Brian?
Well, I remember the storm of 1914, which was a terrible storm, and it was very destructive.
And at that time, my daddy was not working.
He was working on a ranch at another place, and we'd come home over the weekend.
And my mother was always afraid of,
winds, you just couldn't stand them.
And I know that storm blew so hard, it even blew our wagon away from the house.
It took it down across the prairie, and it just tore up everything.
And I was sitting in the bedroom looking at some pictures,
I was just 12 years old, and things like that didn't excite me.
So I was sitting there looking at those pictures, and Mama came in and said, Margie, quick, didn't you see that big tree fall?
It almost hit the house.
And says, we're going to the barn.
We had just finished a new log barn.
And so I said, you think we ought to go?
She said, yes, we need to go.
Says, we've got to get out of here.
So I went out there, and just as I went in the barn door, the top came off.
of the barn and just barely missed my head.
Boy.
And so we were, of course we all had to go back to the house then because we didn't have any shelter over us.
Boy, that's a miracle.
So it was just really a tragic thing.
And Papa came home so upset because everything was just torn to pieces.
And it just ruined everything around the farm.
What kind of storm was this?
Was this a hurricane or something?
Kind of like that.
High winds and rain.
Yeah, real strong winds.
Yeah, storm of 1914.
Yeah, and it just about tore the place down?
Yeah, it sure did.
Was there a lot of damage in Bryan?
Now, I wouldn't know about Brian because, you know, then we didn't have radios and things of that type, and we lived out in the country.
All righty.
Okay.
What changes in technology have you seen, like, you know, transportation and farming, help irrigation, advantages in getting to the market?
Well, there's been lots of changes.
Now, when we lived on the farm and worked on the farm, all we had to work with was mules and walking plows, walking cultivators, and even oxen.
We...
We had a pair of oxen that we drove and plowed.
That's really neat.
I think that would be exciting.
I would like to try that.
Well, I have done it.
I know they were named Coley and Brown.
And Uncle Lewis, he would hollow wool Coley.
And that old oxen knew where to go and what to do.
But nowadays, everything is done by machinery.
That's tractors and machines.
hay balers and hay rakes and all that kind of stuff where we had to do that by hand.
Y'all had to do more of a lot of hard work.
Yeah, we even cut our own corn tops.
We didn't waste anything.
Pop had us save everything.
We cut our corn tops and shocked them, stacked them up in a point like and let them dry and then take them in to feed the cows in the wintertime.
Y'all must have had a lot of crops, right?
Yeah, we raised practically everything we ate except the staples.
like sugar and flour, and even ground our own meal.
We had a great big, what they called then, a potato bank that was built out of logs with dirt over it.
And then we'd put straw in there, inside of it.
And it had a door to it.
And we would store cushions, and turnips, and potatoes, and all that kind of stuff.
We killed all of our meat, and cured our meat, and had our lard.
We even made our syrup.
And all that kind of thing.
We had to do that all by hand, except, of course, that we had a certain mill that squeezed the juice out of the cane, you know.
And it was driven by a mule.
Y'all rode horses, right?
Yeah.
How far out of Bryan did y'all live?
Well, we just didn't come to Bryan.
When we went, we went to Navasota.
We were closer to Navasota.
And we lived about...
I guess about six miles north of Millican.
We lived at what you call the Peach Creek Community.
And that's the way that we did everything.
We did it the hard way.
But we enjoyed it.
I bet y'all did.
That's the only thing y'all knew.
Yeah.
The only thing I didn't like to do
whole sweet potatoes.
It was really hard.
Did y'all have to get up in the morning real early and milk the cows?
We got up and milked about 15 cows before we went to school every morning.
Y'all must have got up early.
Yeah, had to.
Of course, we lived right near the school.
We were lucky to live near the school.
And of course, those days, we had to take our lunch.
Some of us would get up and help Mama fix, you know, cook the stuff for lunches and things.
And she was always so good to always have donuts and things of that kind for us to carry.
And she always kept something sweet cooked.
And an old fellow came around with an old Baptist preacher.
And he sold apples.
And we traded him butter for apples.
And we kept that.
You know how we kept our butter cold?
We had a big dug cistern.
And we would let that butter down, put it in gallon buckets, and let it down with a rope and leave it in that water so it would stay cold.
Oh, that's neat.
We didn't have refrigerators then.
No refrigerators.
No.
We didn't have electricity.
Yeah.
And the job, okay, advantages in getting to the market, you said by horse or whatever?
Well, the only way you had to go then was horse and wagon.
Right.
And nowadays, people have trucks, have hardtop roads, and have cars, and it's just all the difference in the world.
Okay.
When did you start using modern appliances?
Well, where I lived, after I married, I lived at the Tabor community.
And we didn't have electricity out there until 1937, when the REA came out there.
They got the REA organized and put electricity to the rural communities.
And that was the first time we'd had any was in 1937.
That was a long time ago.
I bet that was really exciting, y'all getting that, right?
Yeah.
I'll never forget it.
They went to town and bought a used radio, and they played Bing Crosby.
Until midnight, I never got to start singing my life.
Oh, yeah.
Well, y'all had photographs?
Or, I mean, what do you call them?
Those old record players?
Y'all didn't have that until the electricity came in?
Well, you could have those.
You'd wind them up.
Wind them, right.
Okay.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
We didn't have any natural gas.
And then after we had electricity, we got the butane gas for cooking and heating.
And those were kind of heaven sent to us because we lived out in the rural areas where we had to use coal oil cook stoves.
And they had one fireplace in the house, and you couldn't warm a house that way.
How did y'all heat yourselves?
I mean, keep that place heated?
We had that one fireplace.
Did y'all all sleep around that fireplace?
No.
Or what?
What did y'all do, just cover it in blankets?
Mm-hmm.
We just got cold.
Oh, I bet that was uncomfortable.
It was.
Next question.
What was a normal day like, and what did you do, and when did you go, and what travel to various places?

Well, my normal day was pretty hectic sometimes, because I had several babies and children to take care of, and had to get up about 5.30 in the morning or 6, because we had to fix all the lunches for the children that were in school.
And by the way, I had been, when I married, I had been in school all my life.
I had started school when I was five, and as soon as I got out of school, I took the teacher's examination and taught.
And that was two years of college, right?
And then I went to college and had two years.
Oh, okay.
And then, of course, when I married, I had a stepson then.
He was ready to start school that year, so therefore I was in school continuously.
So the days were really full.
And, of course, we did everything the hard way.
I had to wash with the tub and rub board and things of that type, you know, and carry in wood.
And just everything that could be done had to be done manually.
There's no machinery at all to do anything.
A lot of labor put in that.
You bet.
And it was hard labor, too.
And traveling, we did have vacations occasionally with my sister, Ms. Baker, and her husband.
Only time we ever went vacation was when we went with them.
We always went together.
Where'd y'all go?
Well, we went to the centennial, the year they had that, at Dallas.
And then we went to San Antonio one summer, and we went to all those parks and zoos and things of that type.
And then we went to Mineral Wells, because that was where Mr. Baker, your granddaddy, had lived at one time.
And so we went there one week and spent the week.
And every time we went, well, we went with them.
We went to Galveston and we went to places like that.
Did you ever go far out of state or anything like that?
No, not then we didn't.
The only time I've been out of state was when your grandmother and I, Ms. Baker, went on that bus tour about five years ago.
And we went all up in Canada and Alaska.
Not Alaska.
We didn't go to Alaska.
We went to Canada.
And went to New York, went to Washington, DC, and went through, oh, I don't have any states.
But that's beautiful.
Canada's beautiful.
Yeah, and it's so clean.
And we just enjoyed it so much.
We were gone three weeks.
and went to Nashville and went to the Grand Ole Opera.
I heard that is really something to see.
And went to the Upper Room.
Well, they tell me that the old one wasn't nothing compared to this new one.
You know, they built a new one and have the opera laying.
And this lady told me just a while ago that it was better than any Disney World.
Oh, really?
I'd like to go up there sometime.
That's nice.
We're hoping we can go this spring or this summer.
All righty.
What were the designs of the houses like, and how do they differ from today?
They can, you know, know.
Put some of that down.

Well, houses in those, in the old days, were so much different from ones they are now because most of them were built with two rooms across the front and a long front porch or else two rooms and a big hallway down through the middle and
They had no closets, no storage space, no bathrooms.
And way back there, when you had to take a bath, you had to bring a wash tub in, heat your water on the stove, which was a wood stove at that.
And we just didn't have any hot water, any convenience at all.
And now the houses are so different.
They are made all modern.
Everything is push buttons now.
With every convenience needed, central air and heat,
Telephones, intercom, and you name it, the new homes have it.
Right, more modernized and everything.
And they're much warmer than the houses, the old houses, you froze to death in them because they were so high up off the ground, and the windows, people didn't know how to build houses in those days.
Did y'all have any fireplaces upstairs also?
No, we just had one upstairs.
The basement, did y'all have any basements?
No.
No basement.
Huh.
And the house set up about two and a half feet off the ground.
I remember the kids used to play, you know how they used to play with these little cars?
Right.
That's where they played, under the front porch.
Underneath the front porch, right.
So they had to get where there was some dirt, because we had grass on the yard.
These houses have a lot of, were they more, had columns in the front, or what?
Some of them did, yeah.
Some of them did, or more like that?
Yeah.
All wooded?
Yeah, all wooded.
All wooded, and high seeding.
Yeah.
They were high seeding?
Yeah, they really were.
They said that made them cooler in the summer.
It also made them cooler in the winter.
That's right.
Okay.
What schooling did you have, and how does it differ from today?
Well, the school I went to was a one-teacher school, and we didn't have any bus system or anything in those days, and we were fortunate enough to live close to the school.
It was just right outside of our
Pasture Gate, we just lived right at it.
I guess it wasn't a mile even.
The school?
To the school.
Well, that's good.
And we just had a one-teacher school and went through the seventh grade at that time.
But then later, we built a two-teacher school in the community, and it went through the eighth grade.
And so I worked hard, and I studied at home and everything to...
learned enough that I could pass a teacher's exam.
In those days, you could go for the county board and take a teacher's examination and get your certificate.
And that's the way I taught, was I got me a certificate that way.
And then I went to college two years after I started teaching.
I saved my money and went.
Each year I'd go to college.
And it is
It's very different today, because children have so many advantages going to school.
Right.
They can carpool.
They can carpool, or in countries, they own the bus line, maybe.
Right, get a bus.
Do y'all ride horses?
Education is one of the best things you need in life.
OK. What was it like during the Depression?
Well, the Depression caused lots of hardships on people.
People that had automobiles and trucks and depended on them for a living, they couldn't get any tires.
Maybe when they needed them, the gasoline was rationed, and they couldn't get enough gasoline to carry on their business.
And the flour and sugar.
And different kinds of food were rationed.
You had to have ration stamps for many items, you know.
And if you used up your ration stamps, you just had to do it out until your next ones come out.
And the gasoline was rationed.
And I know sugar was rationed.
And you could just get so much sugar a month.
That's all you could get.
I can imagine.
Big family, too, especially going through that.
And I'm sure...
There was lots of hardships during the Depression that I don't recall because
You know, it's just...
I remember my mother telling me that there was a lot of people committing suicide, like the stock markets dropping and everything like that, and standing in the soup line.
Yeah, there's lots of people had to do that.
A lot of people were really hitting it hard.
Yeah, they really had it hard, and lots of them were out of work.
There was no work for them to do.
That was terrible.
It really was a tragic thing for our country to have to go through, I'll tell you, and
We were blessed, I guess, in lots of ways.
Right.
Y'all must have gotten hit so hard.
All right.
Tell us about your codes for raising your family, and how does it differ from today's standards?
Well, I raised six children, five boys, one girl.
Times were quite different at first.
They went to a rural school through the 10th grade, then to Bryan High to finish.
And later, our rural school was closed, and they all were bused into Bryan.
My family all had their chores to do each evening.
They were also involved in 4-H projects, which kept them busy.
I had an understanding with my children.
No matter what came up, I was always there to listen and help them with their problems.
I always worked with my children.
I found that you could lead better than drive.
Of course, we didn't have the problems of today.
So many cars, dope, and good highways, which make it impossible for them to get around to so many places.
My family grew up knowing college was automatically a part of their schooling.
I had four boys graduate from A&M.
One is a lawyer, one an aeronautical engineer,
One is state representative, and one works for the State Department of Agriculture.
He graduated from Sam Houston State College.
My daughter married an Aggie graduate.
How many daughters do you have?
I just had one.
One daughter.
And he is president of the Hygiene Milk Company in Harlingen, Texas.
Boy, all your sons graduated from A&M, right?
All of them but Danny.
Danny graduated from Sam Houston.
I see.
All righty.
All of them went into the service except one.
Al, they declared a holiday just about a month before he was to leave.
Drafted.
I see.
All right.
What was your first job?
One of my boys I left out.
He's a veterinary doctor.
He must have graduated from A&M, right?
Yeah, he graduated from A&M, went in service, stayed seven and a half years, came back and went back to A&M and graduated as a veterinary doctor.
That's good.
They get good jobs.
He has his own clinic.
That's really good.
That was him that just left.
And he's a veterinarian?
Mm-hmm.
Oh, okay.
Okay, what was your first job in the community, and what was it like?
Well, the first job I had was I was a teacher.
I taught up through the fifth grade in the two-teacher school there at Peace Creek where I was raised.
Uh-huh.
I loved it.
I loved teaching.
It was just something that was just challenging to you.
So I taught the first year there.
Then I went to Tabor, and I taught two years out there.
And that's where I met my husband and married.
And then I never did get to teach anymore because I did not have a degree.
And I never did get to go back to school anymore.
But that was my job then, and then I also
Worked with 4-H for about 25 years.
Adult leader.
And was camp director for several years.
Also had held offices in the church and in the women's society.
And I have been a member of the local church board, Alexander Methodist Church, for about 20 years.
And where I still go to church.
I drive from Bryan out there when I go to church.
Oh, that's nice.
And I enjoyed it a lot.
So you only really taught school for three years?
Three years.
And what grade level was this?
Do you know?
First year, I taught through the fifth.
Next year, I taught through the seventh.
All the grades in a one-teacher school out there close to table.
It wasn't the table school.
Then the next year, I taught in a table school, which was five teachers, and I taught...
the 5th, 6th, and 7th grades.
Did you teach all subjects?
I mean, were you just, okay, this is where, okay, you taught arithmetic and whatever.
Yes, just taught all of them.
Oh, okay.
That's the way teachers had to do those days.
Right, those days.
Nowadays it's different.
That's right.
We sure are different.
Okay.
Was Brian affected by the energy crisis at all?

yes i'm sure brian was affected quite seriously with the energy crisis because we didn't have enough gas for transportation not enough fuel for machinery and to run the different plants that they run by fuel and we had to consume our electricity that is we had to keep the temperature down turn off the lights and
and things of that kind.
And in the homes and businesses, they had to keep the temperature real low to conserve the electricity and all.
And the energy crisis was just really a serious thing because so many people
just never thought about what it really meant to be without it.
They just never had been.
Never been.
And they just thought that, oh, well, it's there.
We got it.
Right.
They just couldn't realize that someday that it wouldn't be there.
I know.
That would have been a casualty for sure.
Yeah.
But I think it's affected everybody.
It has.
It sure has.
All right.
Has crime increased or decreased any?
And has it affected you any?
Well, I think crime is on the increase.
Of course, we have more people now than we used to have.
And we hear a lot more about it.
It's publicized more.
And people are able to get around more than they used to be.
We used to have these hardtop highways and freeways.
and farm-to-market roads and things like that, and they have good cars.
Anybody can commit a crime in Brown and be in Houston in a couple hours and be out of the reach of officers.
Because back in your day, we didn't have that.
And in our days, we didn't have that kind of stuff.
We just didn't know anything about it.
And we have so much dope that's peddled.
and everything till it just makes life more miserable, I think.
Right.
Did y'all have any horse stealing back in y'all's day?
Well, we could have had.
I don't remember any.
Cattle hustling?
Well, I'm sure we had cattle hustling.
But I don't know.
Where we lived, it was more of a community of people just all worked together.
Right.
Y'all didn't even have to lock your doors at night, did you?
No, we never knew what it was to lock a door.
Yeah, today you have to.
And we ran off from any home we didn't lock our doors.
Right.
And if one person got into trouble that is needing some work done, got sick or something, all the community went and worked his crop out for him.
Well, that's really great.
If he's building a barn, they built a barn for him.
And people just worked more in harmony then than they did now.
They were more together.
Yeah, more together.
And more involved.
That's right.
Most people now don't want to get involved with anything.
No, you're right there.
They sure were.
Well, has crime infected you any?
No, the extent of just worrying, I think, is the only thing.
You can't help but worry about youngsters.
And I do have a bunch of young grandsons that are out at night and times like that and going to school and things.
And that way, it helps.

afraid something will happen to them, and that's about the only way it's affected me, because I keep my doors locked, and I'm in before night, and I don't get out after night unless I'm with some of the boys, or they come by to pick me up, take me somewhere.
Have you had any bad casualties with your family?
Well, yes, we had one terrible bad casualty.
It is in 1918.
At least I thought it was bad.
It
wasn't a fatal casualty, but my older brother had gone to the army.
And he'd come home for Christmas holidays.
And in the meantime, after he had left, we had built up

a walk and we had fixed the brick along the side of it and this walk went out to this underground cistern and he didn't know it was there so the next morning he thought oh I think I'll just he told my sisters I think I'll just wake them all up with a Christmas gun so he took the shotgun out and

raised it up to shoot it and he stumbled on one of these bricks and when he did he fell and naturally he stuck his hand out to catch himself and it blew all his hand off and he's lived with one hand all his life and then another one was my nephew my oldest sister's son was fixing to cross the railroad track here in Bryan and it was a
A place where you couldn't see the train coming or anything.
There was a lot of blockage there.
And the garage sat right beside the track.
And he started up on it.
And as he did, the train hit him, hit the car.
And it was weeks.
We just didn't know whether he'd live or not.
Oh, that's true.
But I think prayers were some of the things saved him.
The doctors gave him up.
How bad off?
I mean, was he really...
He's fine now.
Fine now.
I mean, was he in intensive care when this happened?
Well, then they didn't have intensive care.
Oh, that's right.
But he spent a long time ago there, so he married.
And he has been teaching in the Air Force for years and years, ever since he graduated from A&M.
And he's just doing fine.
He's going to retire and come back here this year.
And we'll be happy to have him home.
Well, that's great.
Let's stop here.
Let's see.
What do you think of the fashions today and how they affect you?
Well, the way they affect me is that I can't find any dresses because they make them all short and so tight that women of our age just can't find the clothes that are suitable for us.
And I do think that, of course, they are getting away from the real, real short ones.
Shorts that's going down.
Like they used to have, but I think they're kind of tacky the way they're getting them down three or four inches below the knees.
